  ## Getting started — Quick setup

  These are minimal steps to run the prototype locally. Adjust commands to your environment.

  1.  Clone the repository

      git clone https://github.com/your-username/ReGen-Mapper.git
      cd ReGen-Mapper

  2.  Frontend (example using Node/npm)

      cd frontend
      npm install
      npm start

  3.  Backend (example using Python/Flask)

      cd ../backend
      python -m venv .venv # optional but recommended
      .\.venv\Scripts\Activate # PowerShell: .\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1 if needed
      pip install -r requirements.txt
      flask run

  4.  Environment & API keys

  - Create a .env file (or use your platform secrets manager) to store keys for:
    - GIS provider (Mapbox, Sentinel Hub, etc.)
    - Database URL / Supabase credentials
    - AI provider keys

  ## Development notes

  - Keep the map and data code modular: separate data fetching, rendering, and business logic.
  - Version control: use feature branches and small PRs. Add concise tests for backend endpoints.
  - Local geodata: use lightweight GeoJSON fixtures for UI development to reduce API usage.

  ## Data & Privacy

  - When collecting contributor data, store only what is needed. Consider anonymization options
    for community privacy and comply with local regulations.
  - Document assumptions for CO₂ calculations and make formulas transparent in the dashboard.

  ## Contribution

  Open to collaborators: data scientists, GIS experts, environmental researchers, frontend and
